Merging datasets

We have two datasets, both with observations per hour. The generation data tells us hourly energy use from various sources. The imports data tells us hourly energy use from imports. Say we want a dataset of all energy use by source during this time period. We need to merge the two datasets.

Since the observations are paired perfectly, this will be relatively easy to do. We can use the merge() function in base R.

Merging datasets

Do the following in your code file:

  • Open and read the help file for merge()
  • Merge the two datasets and save the new data frame as ca_energy

Merging datasets

ca_energy <- merge(ca_generation, ca_imports, by="datetime")

Merging datasets

  • This was a fairly simple merging exercise, since the observations are paired perfectly, and there is an “id” variable that is consistent across both datasets.
  • You can specify differently named “id” variables using the by.x = and by.y = argumetns in merge().
  • If an id only has a row in one dataset but not another, the “new” columns for that id will be populated with missing values.
  • For more complicated merging tasks, see dplyr’s suite of join functions (e.g. look up the help file for left_join()).

Tidy data

Principles of “tidy data”:

  1. Each variable must have its own column.
  2. Each observation must have its own row.
  3. Each value must have its own cell.

[Source: Grolemund and Wickham (2017), R for Data Science, Figure 12.1]

Wide vs. long format data

Sometimes, we will want to turn our data into long format, where each observation-variable pair and its associated value are in separate rows. Long format data usually has three columns: an id column, a variable column, and a value column.

This can be useful in several contexts:

  • Storing extremely large datasets with many missing values
  • Doing certain data transformation tasks faster
  • Manipulating the structure of the wide-format data (e.g. renaming variables based on values)
  • Plotted grouped data (we will do this later today)

Wide vs. long format data

Let’s convert the generation data into long format:

ca_generation_long <- gather(ca_generation, key = "variable", value = "value", -datetime)
dim(ca_generation_long)
## [1] 1512    3
head(ca_generation_long)

Part 2: Data transformation with dplyr

What is dplyr?

  • dplyr is an R package for data manipulation developed by R Studio
  • Principles: consistent syntax, meaningful naming conventions, fewer arguments/more functions - It contains verbs that help you transform data in straightforward ways
  • https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/

dplyr verbs

The core functions in dplyr, which are all “verbs” that perform common actions, are:

  • select: select or exclude certain variables
  • filter: subset observations based on conditions
  • arrange: order rows based on conditions
  • mutate: add new variables
  • summarize: reduce multiple observations to a single value (e.g., find the mean of all data, or within groups)

select()

The select() function allows you to select specific columns from a data frame. Note that in all dplyr functions, the data frame is the first argument.

temp <- select(ca_energy, datetime, biomass, biogas)
glimpse(temp)
## Observations: 168
## Variables: 3
## $ datetime <dttm> 2018-09-03 00:00:00, 2018-09-03 01:00:00, 2018-09-03...
## $ biomass  <int> 413, 413, 410, 410, 413, 419, 415, 413, 415, 414, 412...
## $ biogas   <int> 239, 240, 237, 241, 240, 239, 238, 238, 239, 238, 239...

filter()

The filter() function lets you subset observations in a data frame using defined conditions. For example:

filter(ca_energy, solar > 10000, wind > 1000)
##              datetime biogas biomass geothermal large_hydro natural_gas
## 1 2018-09-09 14:00:00    234     399        899    3243.954    7110.046
##   nuclear small_hydro solar wind imports
## 1    2244         273 10085 1410    5127

Exercise 2: filter()

nrow(filter(ca_energy, wind > 500))

## [1] 90

Pipes: dplyr’s magic ingredient

  • This is a pipe: %>%
  • A pipe takes the output
  • Since all dplyr verb functions take a data frame as the first input and output a data frame, you can use multiple verbs in a sequence using pipes
temp <- ca_energy %>% filter(large_hydro > imports) %>% select(datetime, imports)
temp
##              datetime imports
## 1 2018-09-04 16:00:00    5796
## 2 2018-09-05 14:00:00    4061
## 3 2018-09-05 15:00:00    4570
## 4 2018-09-05 16:00:00    5131
## 5 2018-09-06 15:00:00    4509
## 6 2018-09-06 16:00:00    5343

Part 3: Data visualization with ggplot2

What is ggplot?

Part of the tidyverse, ggplot2 is an R package that implements the “grammar of graphics” in R.

In ggplot, graphics are built by supplying data and mapping of data values to aesthetics, and then adding layers that build geometric objects, scales, labels, and more.

What are the advantages of ggplot?

  • Highly customizable and extensible.
  • Designed to work with dplyr and other tidyverse packages.
  • In use for over 10 years, meaning that help is widely available.
  • Wide variety of avilable extensions

Useful resources

  • The ggplot cheatsheet
  • The ggplot reference guide
  • The Data Visualization chapter in the “R for Data Science” book
  • And, of course, the help files that come with the package itself.

Components of a basic plot

  • data: a data frame, provided to the ggplot() function
  • geometric objects: the objects/shapes that you want to plot, indicated through one of the many available geom functions, such as geom_point() or geom_hist()
  • aesthetic mapping: the mapping from the data to the geometric objects, provided in an aes() function nested within the chosen geom function
  • connected with the + operator
ggplot(data = <DATA FRAME>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<VARIABLES>))

Example with a new dataset

Let’s bring in a new dataset called gapminder. Run this code in your code file.

Geometric objects

We have already seen examples of two kinds of plots:

  • Scatterplots, generated with geom_point()
  • Column charts, generated with geom_col()

Let’s see a few more.

Line plots: geom_line()

ca_energy %>%

Interlude: changing geom characteristics

  • In the geom functions, we have only been supplying aesthetic mapping (in aes()).
  • Geom functions can also control characteristics of the geom object, outside the aes() function.
  • In most geoms, we can modulate size= and col=.
  • Let’s try it with the line plot we just made.

Interlude: changing geom characteristics

ca_energy %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=datetime, y=imports), size=1.2, col="red") + 
  labs(title="Energy imports over time", x="Hour", y="Amount imported (MW)")

Area plots: geom_area()

ca_energy %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_area(aes(x=datetime, y=wind), fill="darkblue") + 
  labs(title="Hourly wind power generation, Sept 3-9", x="Hour", y="Output (MW)")

Box plots: geom_boxplot()

ca_energy_long %>% 
  ggplot() +

Visualizing grouped data

  • We often want to visualize multiple variables, or a variable that can be divided into groups, in one graphic.
  • There are two broad principles for visualizing grouped variables in R:
    • Identify a grouping variable in a geom(aes()) using the group = argument, and demarcate the distinct objects created per group in some way.
    • Use facets to generate geometric objects in separate coordinate systems for each group.

Grouped data with colors/fill

Task:
Create a line plot of energy output over time, with separate lines for each source.

Steps:

  1. Supply the data frame ca_energy_long to ggplot().
  2. Add a geom_line() layer and specify x=datetime and y=output.
  3. Also specify that group=source and col=source.
  4. Add a labs() layer.

Grouped data with colors/fill

ca_energy_long %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=datetime, y=value, group=variable, col=variable)) + 
  labs(title="Output by energy source over time", subtitle="Hourly data from September 3-9, 2018", x="Hour", y="Output (MW)")

Exercise 4: Grouped data with colors/fill

Create a line plot that compares generation of wind and solar energy over time.

Exercise 4: Colors and fill

ca_energy_long %>%
  filter(variable=="wind"|variable=="solar") %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=datetime, y=value, group=variable, col=variable), size=1.5) +

A note on colors and fill

  • col= is used to color objects like lines and points
  • fill= is used to color objects like columns and histograms
  • After some trial and error, this will become intuitive

Grouped data with position adjustment

Colors and fill are the most common method to demarcate grouped data. Position adjustment is the next most common.

Example: Energy use by day

Task:
Create a column chart of energy use by day, grouped by source.

Steps:

  1. Modify ca_energy_long to summarize output by date and source.
    1. Use mutate() to create a date variable from datetime.
    2. Use group_by() and summarize() to calculate total output per date per source.
  2. Supply modified data frame to ggplot()
  3. Add a geom_col() layer, supply x and y aesthetics.
  4. Specify group=source and fill=source.
  5. Add a labs() layer.

Example: Energy use by day

ca_energy_long %>% 
  mutate(date=date(datetime)) %>% 
  group_by(date, variable) %>% 
  summarize(value=sum(value)) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_col(aes(x=date, y=value, group=variable, fill=variable)) + 
  labs(title="Energy use by day", x="Day", y="Output (MW)")

Example: Energy use by day

  • This column chart is useful if our main goal is to examine total output over time across sources.
  • But what if our main goal is to compare trends across sources?
    • We can use position="dodge" in geom_col() ‘unstack’ the columns for each source.
  • What if our goal is to compare what portion of output per day each source comprises?
    • We can use position="fill" to normalize height of stacked columns.

Example: Energy use by day (pos dodge)

ca_energy_long %>% 
  mutate(date=date(datetime)) %>% 
  group_by(date, variable) %>% 
  summarize(value=sum(value)) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_col(aes(x=date, y=value, group=variable, fill=variable), position="dodge") + 
  labs(title="Energy use by day", x="Day", y="Output (MW)")

Example: Energy use by day (pos fill)

ca_energy_long %>% 
  mutate(date=date(datetime)) %>% 
  group_by(date, variable) %>% 
  summarize(value=sum(value)) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_col(aes(x=date, y=value, group=variable, fill=variable), position="fill") + 
  labs(title="Energy use by day", x="Day", y="Output (MW)")

Facets

  • So far we have been visualizing grouped data by changing the appearance or position of the objects.
  • A different approach is to use facets, which creates separate coordinate systems for each geometric object.

Example: Comparing generation patterns

Task:
Compare energy generation over time, across sources.

How do we do this? Using what we’ve learned so far:

  1. Supply ca_energy_long to ggplot().
  2. Add a geom_line() layer, setting x=datetime and y=output in aes().
  3. Let’s set group=source and col=source in aes().

Example: Comparing generation patterns

ca_energy_long %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=datetime, y=value, group=variable, col=variable), size=1) + 
  labs(title="Generation over time, by energy source", subtitle="Hourly data from September 3-9, 2018", x="Hour", y="Output (MW)")

Example: Comparing generation patterns

Is this a helpful plot?

  • Not if our goal is to compare the patterns of each source.
  • It’s too noisy!
  • Instead of setting col= in aes(), let’s add a facet_wrap() layer.
  • Specifically, facet_wrap(~variable), i.e. tell ggplot to “facet by variable”.

Example: Comparing generation patterns

ca_energy_long %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x = datetime, y = value)) + 
  facet_wrap(~variable) + 
  labs(title="Generation over time, by energy source", subtitle="Hourly data from September 3-9, 2018", x="Hour", y="Output (MW)")

Example: Comparing generation patterns

ca_energy_long %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x = datetime, y = value)) + 
  facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free") + 
  labs(title="Generation over time, by energy source", subtitle="Hourly data from September 3-9, 2018", x="Hour", y="Output (MW)")

Compare generation patterns for each source in facets. Color the lines using the “group” variable in ca_groups.

ca_groups <- read_csv("data/ca_groups.csv") 
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   type = col_character(),
##   group = col_character()
## )
ca_energy_long_groups <- merge(ca_energy_long, ca_groups, by.x="variable", by.y="type")

Exercise 6: Facets

ca_energy_long_groups %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=datetime, y=value, group=group, col=group), size=1) + 
  facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free") + 
  labs(title="Generation over time, by energy source", subtitle="Hourly data from September 3-9, 2018", x="Hour", y="Output (MW)") + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Final notes

  • Always remember to comment your code! When writing particularly complex code in dplyr or ggplot2, this includes commenting within a flow of %>% or + operators. See the lecture notes for some examples of this.
  • You can save a plot in two ways: using the “save” icon in the Plots tab of RStudio, or adding ggsave() as a layer to your plotting code.
